argumentText:
The idea is to prove the cosines law:
$$a^2 = b^2 + c^2 - 2bc\cos\theta$$ where the variables are defined by
the triangle: $$\begin{xy}
,(0,0)
;(40,0)**@{-}
;(60,30)**@{-}
;(0,0)**@{-}
,(20,-3)*{c}
,(7,2)*{\theta}
,(50,12)*{a}
,(30,17)*{b}
\end{xy}$$

Let’s add a couple of lines and two variables, to get $$\begin{xy}
,(0,0)
;(40,0)**@{-}
;(60,30)**@{-}
;(0,0)**@{-}
,(20,-3)*{c}
,(7,2)*{\theta}
,(50,12)*{a}
,(30,17)*{b}
,(40,0)
;(60,0)**@{--}
;(60,30)**@{--}
,(50,-3)*{x}
,(63,15)*{y}
\end{xy}$$

This is all we need. We can use Pythagoras’ theorem to show that
$$a^2 = x^2 + y^2$$ and $$b^2 = y^2 + \left(c+x\right)^2$$

So, combining these two we get $$\begin{aligned}
a^2 & = & x^2 + b^2 - \left(c+x\right)^2\\
a^2 & = & x^2 + b^2 - c^2 - 2cx - x^2\\
a^2 & = & b^2 - c^2 - 2cx\end{aligned}$$

So, all we need now is an expression for $x$. Well, we can use the
definition of the cosine function to show that $$\begin{aligned}
c + x & = & b \cos\theta\\
x & = & b\cos\theta - c\end{aligned}$$

With this result in hand, we find that $$\begin{aligned}
a^2 & = & b^2 - c^2 - 2cx\nonumber\\
a^2 & = & b^2 - c^2 - 2c\left( b\cos\theta - c\right)\nonumber\\
a^2 & = & b^2 - c^2 -2bc\cos\theta + 2c^2\nonumber\\
a^2 & = & b^2 + c^2 - 2bc\cos\theta\end{aligned}$$
